<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1323,284,430]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
In the key to Neotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[563,703,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[563,703,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Puliciphora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[816,987,284,310]" pageId="9" pageNumber="53" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2003 a) Seven new species of New World Puliciphora Dahl (Diptera: Phoridae) with a new key to the Neotropical species. Zootaxa, 162, 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="2003" yearSuffix="a">
Disney, 
<number box="[913,973,284,310]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="2003.0">2003</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
) this species will readily run to couplet 
<number box="[391,423,324,350]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="27.0">27</number>
, lead 
<number box="[495,510,324,350]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="2.0">2</number>
to 
<taxonomicName box="[550,690,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecilla">
<emphasis box="[550,690,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. imbecilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as does the new species 
<emphasis box="[998,1170,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName box="[998,1162,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jacquemart">P. jacquemart</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1162,1170,324,350]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">i</emphasis>
</emphasis>
(see above), and is then best distinguished by its possession of small wing rudiments (similar to 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 24" captionStartId="13.[264,383,1275,1299]" captionTargetBox="[542,979,702,1231]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[506,1081,689,1249]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 24. Puliciphora triangularis: (22) female, abdominal tergite 5; (23) female, right wing rudiment; (24) male, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/169853/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
Fig. 
<number box="[264,294,404,430]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="23.0">23</number>
</figureCitation>
) and T 
<number box="[378,392,404,430]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="6.0">6</number>
being represented by its anterior apodemes only.
</paragraph>
